Comment: I can only hope the best for this.Â  The trailer does not give us any real scoop on the plot, if any.Â  I personally enjoyed two franchises loads of people really loved, or really hated that utilized this kind of world:Â  AATC and FiM.Â  A series in a world where high pitched, flat nosed dwarfs exist alongside other people, and another set in a world populated by cute but creepy little horses with marks on their hides.Â  The backlash against the Chipmunks was every bit as powerful as the fandom.Â  The scrutiny that Ponies continue to receive is staggering, yet that doesn't stop fictions and visual arts from being churned out on DA amongst others.Â  Will this movie be a turning point, or will it become a silly fad like the chipmunks and ponies did in two years or less? I can say one thing: It won't make me appreciate Anthro art any less, any more than EQG and AATC 2007 and 2009 made me love chipmunks and ponies any less.Â  If the story pleases me, then I will praise David Seville, Beatrice Miller and Celestia for a great film.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: This looks great, but Disney, nothing we've ever seen "be-fur?" Bad pun aside, we have all seen this before. Disney, YOU have used anthropomorphic creatures in almost all of your movies. This concept itself, of a world made of entirely anthropomorphic animals, is also /not/ an original idea, which you seem to be attempting to pass it off as. There's this thing called the "furry community" (an actually great crowd full of good people that has an unfortunate and unjustified reputation). I'm not complaining, stories/worlds like this are great! And the furry community could definitely use some positive exposure. I just feel like it's kind of a kick in the leg to the countless people who have made stories and graphic novels like this when you say it's "like nothing seen before." Other than that little line, this seems amazing, and I'm pretty excited for it! I'd just be nice if you stopped advertising it in a way that makes it seem like you're trying to sell it as an original concept. Not sure if that was your intent or not, but that's the feeling I got from watching the trailer.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment:
I give Disney major kudos for making a movie using the term "anthropomorphic" correctly, as well as shooting for an original anthropomorphic film period.

So I won't rain on their parade and mention PlayStation's Sly Cooper, Hanna Barbera's SWAT Kats, Nintendo's Star Fox, Dreamwork's Kung Fu Panda or Nickolodeon's Tuff Puppy.

And before anyone says anything, no Barnyard and Nut Job don't count because there are still humans. And certain 50's cartoons with talking animals that act as the mascot for certain mystery solving groups don't count either.

Reading the plot from the description, the only way I can see it being interesting is if the small herbivore versus big carnivore animals were symbolism to racism or some sort of discrimination but if it's only the rabbit that is being bullied then the idea of this doesn't seem that original to me.
